## Chemical compound

[Turpentine](/Turpentine), burdened by an excessive number of aliases—including [spirit of turpentine](/Turpentine), [oil of turpentine](/Turpentine), terebenthine, terebenthene, terebinthine, and the utterly common "turps" &#91;2&#93;—is, at its core, a fluid obtained through the rather insistent process of [distillation](/Distillation). This extraction targets the [resin](/Resin) that living [trees](/Tree), predominantly various species of [pine](/Pine), exude. Its primary function, for those who still find practical applications for such things, is as a specialized [solvent](/Solvent). Beyond merely dissolving substances, it also begrudgingly offers itself as a foundational material for various intricate [organic syntheses](/Organic_synthesis).

The chemical composition of [turpentine](/Turpentine) is dominated by [terpenes](/Terpene), those fascinating [organic compounds](/Organic_compound) derived from isoprene units. Specifically, it's primarily composed of the [monoterpenes](/Monoterpene) [α-pinene](/%CE%91-pinene) and [β-pinene](/%CE%92-pinene). Lesser, yet still significant, quantities of other [terpenes](/Terpene) are also present, including [carene](/Carene), [camphene](/Camphene), [limonene](/Limonene), and [terpinolene](/Terpinolene) &#91;3&#93;. This blend of [terpenes](/Terpene) is what gives [turpentine](/Turpentine) its characteristic odor and solvent properties.

In a twist of industrial convenience, [turpentine](/Turpentine) is now rarely the direct product of harvesting and distilling [pine resin](/Resin). Instead, it has largely become a byproduct, an ancillary offering, of the [pulping](/Pulp_(paper)) industry. [Pulping](/Pulp_(paper)) itself is achieved predominantly through two distinct industrial processes: the [Kraft process](/Kraft_process) (also known as the sulfate process) and the [sulfite process](/Sulfite_process). It's worth noting that the [turpentines](/Turpentine) yielded by these two methods are not identical; their chemical compositions diverge. The [sulfite process](/Sulfite_process) typically produces a [turpentine](/Turpentine) that is notably rich in [cymene](/Cymene), while the more prevalent [Kraft process](/Kraft_process) yields a product that retains its historical richness in [pinene](/Pinene) &#91;4&#93;.

For those seeking alternatives, perhaps due to cost or a preference for less natural, more synthetic compounds, substitutes exist. The most common among these are [white spirit](/White_spirit) and other [petroleum](/Petroleum) distillates &#91;5&#93;. However, one should be clear: while they may serve similar functional purposes as [solvents](/Solvent), their underlying chemical constituents are vastly different. Expecting the same properties from chemically distinct substances is, frankly, a fool's errand.

## Etymology

The journey of the word "[turpentine](/Turpentine)" itself is a rather convoluted one, tracing its lineage (via [French](/French_language) and [Latin](/Latin)) back to the venerable [Greek language](/Greek_language). Specifically, it stems from the [Greek](/Greek_language) word *τερεβινθίνη*, which translates to *terebinthine* in English &#91;6&#93;. This, in turn, is the feminine form (a grammatical quirk to align with the [feminine gender](/Grammatical_gender) of the [Greek](/Greek_language) word for 'resin') of an adjective (*τερεβίνθινος*) derived from the [Greek](/Greek_language) noun *τερέβινθος*, which refers to the [terebinth](/Terebinth) tree &#91;6&#93;. A rather circuitous route for a simple word, wouldn't you agree? Humans and their languages, always overcomplicating things.

Initially, the term referred quite literally to the resinous exudate—the sticky, aromatic goo—produced by [terebinth trees](/Terebinth). Examples of this original usage include [Chios turpentine](/Pistacia_lentiscus), [Cyprus turpentine](/Cyprus_turpentine), and [Persian turpentine](/Pistacia_atlantica) &#91;7&#93; &#91;8&#93;. However, as is often the case with human terminology, its meaning broadened and shifted over time. Today, the word "[turpentine](/Turpentine)" almost exclusively refers to the [resin](/Resin) from [coniferous](/Conifer) trees—primarily [pines](/Pine)—which is known as [crude turpentine](/Crude_turpentine) (for instance, [Venice turpentine](/Venice_turpentine) is the [oleoresin](/Oleoresin) of the [larch](/Larch)) &#91;9&#93;. More commonly still, it refers to the [volatile oil](/Volatile_oil) fraction of this [crude turpentine](/Crude_turpentine), specifically the [oil (spirit) of turpentine](/Turpentine) &#91;10&#93;. The latter usage is, by far, the dominant understanding today, leaving the original [terebinth](/Terebinth)-derived meaning largely to the dusty annals of etymological history.

## Source trees

