*A worker "chipping" a [turpentine tree](/Turpentine) in Georgia (US), sometime between 1906 and 1920. A rather crude method, but effective, if you don't mind scarring the landscape.*

![Cat face on a pine tree](/File:Cat_face_pine.jpg)
*The distinctive "Cat face" scar on a [pine tree](/Pine), a visible testament to past [turpentine](/Turpentine) harvesting. A permanent mark of human industry.*

![Turpentine distillery at Manlyn, North Carolina](/File:Turpentine_distillery_Manlyn_North_Carolina.jpg)
*A [turpentine distillery](/Turpentine) operating at Manlyn, North Carolina. The industrial scale of extraction, turning forest bounty into commercial product.*

The primary botanical sources, the unfortunate species designated by humans to yield this particular fluid, are various types of [pine](/Pine). These include, but are not limited to, the [maritime pine](/Pinus_pinaster) (*[Pinus pinaster](/Pinus_pinaster)*), the [Aleppo pine](/Pinus_halepensis) (*[Pinus halepensis](/Pinus_halepensis)*), [Masson's pine](/Pinus_massoniana) (*[Pinus massoniana](/Pinus_massoniana)*), the [Sumatran pine](/Pinus_merkusii) (*[Pinus merkusii](/Pinus_merkusii)*), the [longleaf pine](/Longleaf_pine) (*Pinus palustris*), the [loblolly pine](/Pinus_taeda) (*[Pinus taeda](/Pinus_taeda)*), the [slash pine](/Pinus_elliottii) (*[Pinus elliottii](/Pinus_elliottii)*), and the [ponderosa pine](/Pinus_ponderosa) (*[Pinus ponderosa](/Pinus_ponderosa)*). These species, spread across various continents, have all been tapped, quite literally, for their valuable [resin](/Resin) content, forming the backbone of historical [turpentine](/Turpentine) production.

## Converting crude turpentine to oil of turpentine

*   See also: [Rosin § Purification](/Rosin)

The journey from the raw, sticky [crude turpentine](/Crude_turpentine) collected directly from the [trees](/Tree) to the refined [oil of turpentine](/Turpentine) involves a rather straightforward, if somewhat archaic, process. Typically, this crude material is subjected to [steam distillation](/Steam_distillation) within a [copper](/Copper) still &#91;11&#93;. During this process, the more [volatile](/Volatile) components—the very essence of [turpentine](/Turpentine)—are vaporized, then condensed and collected, leaving behind the less [volatile](/Volatile), solid residue. This residue, once the [turpentine](/Turpentine) has been meticulously distilled out, remains in the still bottoms as molten [rosin](/Rosin) &#91;11&#93;. The resulting [turpentine](/Turpentine) from this specific method of extraction is often referred to as "[gum turpentine](/Turpentine)" &#91;12&#93;. However, a word of caution: the term "[gum turpentine](/Turpentine)" can also, confusingly, be used to refer to the initial [crude turpentine](/Crude_turpentine) itself, a linguistic imprecision that, frankly, serves no one &#91;12&#93;.

Alternatively, [turpentine](/Turpentine) can be obtained through the more aggressive method of [destructive distillation](/Destructive_distillation) of [pine wood](/Pine_wood) &#91;3&#93;. This involves heating the wood, often in the form of shredded [pine stumps](/Pine_stump), roots, or logging slash, in the absence of [oxygen](/Oxygen), forcing it to break down into various components. From this process, the desired [turpentine](/Turpentine) is then extracted using the lighter fraction of heavy [naphtha](/Naphtha) from an [oil refinery](/Oil_refinery), specifically the portion boiling between 90 and 115 °C (195 and 240 °F) &#91;13&#93;. To maximize efficiency and yield, a multi-stage [counter-current extraction](/Solid_phase_extraction) system is commonly employed. In this sophisticated setup, fresh [naphtha](/Naphtha) is first brought into contact with [wood](/Wood) that has already undergone some leaching in previous stages. Conversely, [naphtha](/Naphtha) already laden with [turpentine](/Turpentine) from earlier stages is directed towards fresh [wood](/Wood), ensuring optimal saturation. Following this extraction, [vacuum distillation](/Vacuum_distillation) is utilized to meticulously recover the [naphtha](/Naphtha) from the [turpentine](/Turpentine) &#91;13&#93;. Even after this, the leached [wood](/Wood) isn't simply discarded; it's often steamed to recover any residual [naphtha](/Naphtha) before being burned for [energy recovery](/Energy_recovery) &#91;13&#93;. This [turpentine](/Turpentine) derived from wood is distinctly known as "[wood turpentine](/Turpentine)."

## Sulfate turpentine

In the grand scheme of industrial efficiency, or perhaps just a pragmatic approach to waste, [sulfate turpentine](/Turpentine) emerges as a notable byproduct. When the chemical [wood pulp](/Wood_pulp) is produced from [pines](/Pine) or other [coniferous trees](/Coniferous_trees) using the [Kraft process](/Kraft_process)—a method that, despite its somewhat aggressive nature, is remarkably effective—[sulfate turpentine](/Turpentine) can be condensed from the gases generated within the [pulp digesters](/Kraft_process) &#91;14&#93;. The average yield of this [crude sulfate turpentine](/Turpentine) is typically in the range of 5–10 kg per tonne of [pulp](/Pulp_(paper)) produced &#91;14&#93;.

While a valuable resource, [sulfate turpentine](/Turpentine) isn't always ready for immediate deployment. Unless it's destined to be burned directly at the mill for [energy production](/Energy_production)—a rather ignominious end for a chemical compound—it often necessitates further treatment. This additional processing is crucial for removing trace amounts of [sulfur](/Sulfur) compounds &#91;15&#93;. These [sulfur](/Sulfur) impurities, if left unchecked, can impart undesirable odors and affect the quality of the [turpentine](/Turpentine) for subsequent applications. It's a testament to the persistent nature of byproducts: even after being extracted, they often demand further attention before becoming truly useful.

## Uses

Humans, ever resourceful in their pursuit of utility, have found a rather diverse, if sometimes questionable, array of applications for [turpentine](/Turpentine).

### Solvent

As a [solvent](/Solvent), [turpentine](/Turpentine) has traditionally been employed for thinning [oil-based paints](/Paint), allowing for easier application and manipulation of pigments. It also plays a crucial role in the production of various [varnishes](/Varnish), lending them their characteristic flow and finish. Beyond these more artistic and decorative applications, it serves as a fundamental raw material within the broader [chemical industry](/Chemical_industry), a starting point for more complex syntheses.

However, in the relentless march of industrialized nations towards cost-efficiency, its reign as a dominant [solvent](/Solvent) has largely been usurped. Cheaper [turpentine substitutes](/Turpentine_substitute), derived from [petroleum](/Petroleum)—such as the ubiquitous [white spirit](/White_spirit)—have stepped in to fill the void &#91;5&#93;. Humans, it seems, will always prioritize the bottom line, even if it means sacrificing the unique properties of a natural product for a synthetic alternative. On a more domestic front, a solution of [turpentine](/Turpentine) mixed with either [beeswax](/Beeswax) or [carnauba wax](/Carnauba_wax) has long been a favored formulation for furniture waxes, offering both protection and a degree of shine. A quaint, if rather sticky, tradition.

### Lighting

In a bygone era, specifically from the 1830s through the 1860s, a refined form of [turpentine](/Turpentine) known as [camphine](/Camphine) (or [spirits of turpentine](/Turpentine)) found a rather flammable application: it was burned in lamps, typically those equipped with glass chimneys, to produce illumination &#91;16&#93;. For those who desired a slightly different, perhaps more potent, fuel, [turpentine](/Turpentine) was blended with [grain alcohol](/Grain_alcohol) to create what was then known as "burning fluid" &#91;17&#93;. Both [camphine](/Camphine) and this "burning fluid" served as common domestic lamp fuels, gradually displacing the once-dominant [whale oil](/Whale_oil) as a source of light &#91;17&#93;. Their prominence, however, was fleeting, as they were eventually, and quite decisively, superseded by the advent of [kerosene](/Kerosene), the broader implementation of [gas lighting](/Gas_lighting), and, ultimately, the transformative power of [electric lights](/Electric_lights) &#91;17&#93;. A brief moment in the sun, one might say, for a rather pungent illuminant.

### Source of organic compounds

Beyond its role as a [solvent](/Solvent), [turpentine](/Turpentine) also functions as a surprisingly rich source of raw materials for the synthesis of various fragrant [chemical compounds](/Chemical_compound). A rather ironic twist, considering its own often-overpowering aroma. Commercially significant compounds such as [camphor](/Camphor), [linalool](/Linalool), [alpha-terpineol](/Terpineol), and [geraniol](/Geraniol)—all highly valued for their distinctive scents and industrial applications—are typically derived from the [alpha-pinene](/Alpha-pinene) and [beta-pinene](/Beta-pinene) components of [turpentine](/Turpentine) &#91;3&#93;. These [pinenes](/Pinene), being the chief chemical constituents, are meticulously separated and purified through careful [distillation](/Distillation) processes. What remains after this selective extraction—a mixture primarily composed of [diterpenes](/Diterpene) and [triterpenes](/Triterpene)—is not wasted. This residue is then marketed and utilized as [rosin](/Rosin), proving that even the leftovers of [turpentine](/Turpentine) production possess their own distinct commercial value.

### Niche uses

Ah, the "niche uses." Where humans get truly creative, or perhaps just desperate, with their applications.

*   Given its inherent nature as a [pine pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) thinner, [turpentine](/Turpentine) proves remarkably effective at removing stubborn [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) from clothing. Other common [solvents](/Solvent) often fall short in this specific task, highlighting [turpentine's](/Turpentine) targeted efficacy.
*   [Turpentine](/Turpentine) finds its way into numerous cleaning and sanitary products, not just for its [solvent](/Solvent) capabilities, but due to its recognized [antiseptic](/Antiseptic) properties and, rather subjectively, its "clean scent." A scent that, to some, might simply evoke memories of industrial cleaning, but to each their own.
*   As previously noted, in early 19th-century America, [spirits of turpentine](/Turpentine) (known as [camphine](/Camphine)) were a cheap alternative to [whale oil](/Whale_oil) for lamps &#91;16&#93;. It provided a bright light, certainly, but came with the rather significant drawback of a potent, lingering odor. [Camphine](/Camphine) and [burning fluid](/Camphine) (a mixture of [alcohol](/Grain_alcohol) and [turpentine](/Turpentine)) served as the dominant lamp fuels, briefly, replacing [whale oil](/Whale_oil) until the inevitable arrival of [kerosene](/Kerosene), [electric lights](/Electric_lights), and [gas lighting](/Gas_lighting) &#91;17&#93;. Progress, as always, marches on.
*   In a rather fascinating historical footnote, the first [Honda](/Honda) motorcycles, manufactured in 1946 amidst the scarcity following [World War II](/World_War_II) in Japan, were powered by a blend of [gasoline](/Gasoline) and [turpentine](/Turpentine) &#91;18&#93;. A testament to necessity breeding unconventional fuel solutions. Similarly, the [French](/French_language) [Emeraude rocket](/Emeraude_(rocket)) utilized a comparable fuel mixture &#91;19&#93;. More recently, [turpentine](/Turpentine) has even been explored as a potential [biofuel](/Biofuel) component for blending into [gasoline](/Gasoline) &#91;20&#93; &#91;21&#93;, demonstrating a cyclical interest in this ancient substance.
*   The esteemed veterinarian and author [James Herriot](/James_Herriot), in his book *[If Only They Could Talk](/All_Creatures_Great_and_Small_(franchise))*, recounts a rather theatrical use of [turpentine](/Turpentine). He describes its reaction with [resublimed](/Sublimation_(phase_transition)) [iodine](/Iodine) to "drive the [iodine](/Iodine) into the tissue" &#91;22&#93;. Or, as one might cynically observe, perhaps just to impress the watching customer with a spectacular, dense cloud of purple smoke &#91;22&#93;. A touch of showmanship in veterinary medicine, it seems.

## Safety and health considerations

![NFPA 704 safety square](/File:NFPA_704_Proposed_Turpentine.svg)
*The [NFPA 704](/NFPA_704) safety square for [turpentine](/Turpentine). Pay attention, or don't. It's your [central nervous system](/Central_nervous_system) at stake, not mine.*

*   [1](/NFPA_704) (Health): Minimal hazard under normal conditions, but capable of causing irritation.
*   [3](/NFPA_704) (Flammability): Highly flammable.
*   [0](/NFPA_704) (Instability): Stable.

Let's be clear: [turpentine](/Turpentine) is not something to be trifled with. It is, to put it mildly, highly flammable. So much so, in fact, that it has genuinely been considered as an automotive fuel. A rather spirited, if dangerous, choice.

Perhaps one of the most egregious historical misuses of [turpentine](/Turpentine) occurred during the infamous [Gin Craze](/Gin_Craze) in 18th-century Britain. During this period of rampant [gin](/Gin) consumption, [turpentine](/Turpentine) was extensively, and quite irresponsibly, added to the spirit &#91;23&#93;. A charming addition, I'm sure, for those who enjoyed chemical burns with their libations.

The dangers of [turpentine](/Turpentine) extend far beyond its flammability. Its vapor alone is a significant irritant, capable of causing discomfort to the [skin](/Skin) and [eyes](/Eye). Inhaling these vapors can lead to damage to the delicate tissues of the [lungs](/Lungs) and the broader [respiratory system](/Respiratory_system), as well as insidious harm to the [central nervous system](/Central_nervous_system) &#91;24&#93;. Should one be foolish enough to ingest it, the consequences are even more severe. Ingestion can induce immediate, excruciating burning sensations, intense [abdominal pain](/Abdominal_pain), [nausea](/Nausea), and violent [vomiting](/Vomiting) &#91;25&#93;. Furthermore, it can lead to mental confusion, frightening [convulsions](/Convulsion), debilitating [diarrhea](/Diarrhea), a dangerously elevated [heart rate](/Tachycardia) ([tachycardia](/Tachycardia)), unconsciousness, and even outright [respiratory failure](/Respiratory_failure) &#91;25&#93;. To top it all off, it is a known culprit in causing [chemical pneumonia](/Chemical_pneumonitis) &#91;25&#93;. A truly comprehensive list of ways to make oneself miserable, wouldn't you agree?

Recognizing these hazards, regulatory bodies have established guidelines for its handling. The US [Occupational Safety and Health Administration](/Occupational_Safety_and_Health_Administration) (OSHA) has stipulated a legal limit, known as the [permissible exposure limit](/Permissible_exposure_limit), for [turpentine](/Turpentine) exposure in the workplace. This limit is set at 100 ppm (equivalent to 560 mg/m³) over an 8-hour workday. This exact threshold was also adopted by the [National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health](/National_Institute_for_Occupational_Safety_and_Health) (NIOSH) as their [recommended exposure limit](/Recommended_exposure_limit) (REL) &#91;26&#93;. However, it's critical to note that at concentrations of 800 ppm (or 4480 mg/m³), [turpentine](/Turpentine) is deemed [immediately dangerous to life and health](/IDLH) &#91;26&#93;. So, perhaps exercise a modicum of caution, if self-preservation is a concept you're familiar with.

## Folk medicine

Ah, [folk medicine](/Traditional_medicine). That delightful realm where desperate humans, lacking scientific understanding, experimented with whatever substances were at hand. [Turpentine](/Turpentine), along with other [petroleum distillates](/Petroleum_distillate) like [coal oil](/Coal_oil) and [kerosene](/Kerosene), was once a common fixture in this arena &#91;27&#93;. It was applied to abrasions and wounds, presumably for its purported [antiseptic](/Antiseptic) qualities, and even used as a rather aggressive treatment for [lice](/Lice) &#91;27&#93;. When combined with [animal fat](/Animal_fat), it transformed into a chest rub or an inhalant, intended to alleviate nasal and throat ailments &#91;28&#93;. Curiously, some modern [chest rubs](/Chest_rub), such as [Vicks VapoRub](/Vicks_VapoRub), still contain [turpentine](/Turpentine) in their formulations, though it is no longer listed as an active ingredient &#91;29&#93;. A lingering ghost of past medical practices, perhaps.

Perhaps even more alarmingly, [turpentine](/Turpentine), which we now understand to be unequivocally dangerous for consumption, was a surprisingly common medicine among seamen during the expansive [Age of Discovery](/Age_of_Discovery) &#91;30&#93;. It was, in fact, one of the many provisions carried aboard [Ferdinand Magellan](/Ferdinand_Magellan)'s fleet during their audacious [first circumnavigation of the globe](/First_circumnavigation_of_the_globe) &#91;30&#93;. Taken internally—a decision one can only describe as profoundly misguided—it was used as a supposed treatment for [intestinal parasites](/Intestinal_parasite) &#91;31&#93;. This practice, as should be glaringly obvious, was exceedingly dangerous due to the inherent [toxicity](/Toxicity) of the chemical &#91;32&#93;. One can only imagine the additional suffering endured in the name of "cure."

And then, there are [turpentine enemas](/Enema). A truly harsh purgative, formerly employed for cases of stubborn [constipation](/Constipation) or severe fecal impaction &#91;33&#93;. As if the internal consumption wasn't enough, humans found another, even more invasive, route for this toxic substance. In a darker historical note, these same enemas were, with chilling brutality, administered punitively to political dissenters in post-independence Argentina &#91;34&#93;. A stark reminder that the applications of substances, however benign their initial intent, can quickly descend into cruelty.

